spanGrp.span: ‘A monkey and a child began to play together;
Sãl jãmẽ e-gla yaba jẽk kaga jinõ jela ñara í
Suddely the monkey went somewhere, it looked for it.
Jueta mãĩ sãl mẽnẽũ-mĩ í yulö (m)
he found some ants and ate them;
Je të sawak kwã' je jie të sawak katá
the child could not eat them.
He then left and found some bananas, ripe ones.
Tögapa mẽnẽũ-mĩ-nẽ të chomõ kwã' chomõli kwã'-ite
The child ate and then his [the monkey’s] body itched and fell down;
Yaba të ñã' kepa (_) í wakwa yaka blõnã' tlãka í (m) yaka janã-mĩ
it itched so much that he had to scratch himself with a stone.
í yaka blõnã'ũ-te mẽ tã'ĩ Biá-ite jak mẽ
jebi yaba yulei të í kömanẽwe-gate
after scratching a lot, he fell asleep.
Kepa tanto í jẽk biá-bi í kepenã' janã-mĩ
He then fell into the water;
there the child fell down on top of the monkey.
Jeska yaba yulei je të kã'tiá ĩã janã-ka sãl bata inga
They went down and got to the river; a huge fox appeared before them
Í mẽnẽũ-lo damĩũ-lo diglö inga bi mãĩ böglí tã'ĩ desãũ í wö inga
he dropped both of them on the river.
je të í jãwã-mĩ b-ol wekke diglö jãrga
They went down, the child was drawning in the river and so was the monkey.’
Í mẽnẽũ-lo-mĩ bi yaba siwã' ẽr-gate diglö jãrga jebi sãl jiebi
